{
  "meta": {
    "brand": "Orbital",
    "course": "MAT345",
    "topic": "Every Group of Order 15 is Cyclic",
    "product_family": "Orbital Proof"
  },
  "intro_duration": 2.0,
  "steps": [
    {
      "step": 0,
      "narration": "Let's prove that every group of order fifteen is cyclic, without using the Sylow theorems.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "Every group of order 15 is cyclic.",
      "type": "box",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "Theorem",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_00.mp3",
      "duration": 5.8
    },
    {
      "step": 1,
      "narration": "Let G be a group with order fifteen. Note that fifteen factors as three times five.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "Let $G$ be a group with $|G| = 15 = 3 \\cdot 5$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_01.mp3",
      "duration": 5.8
    },
    {
      "step": 2,
      "narration": "By Cauchy's Theorem, since three divides the order of G,",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "By Cauchy's Theorem, since 3 divides $|G|$,",
      "type": "text",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_02.mp3",
      "duration": 3.67
    },
    {
      "step": 3,
      "narration": "there exists an element a in G of order three.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "$\\exists\\, a \\in G$ with $\\text{ord}(a) = 3$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_03.mp3",
      "duration": 3.25
    },
    {
      "step": 4,
      "narration": "Similarly, since five divides the order of G,",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "Similarly, since 5 divides $|G|$,",
      "type": "text",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_04.mp3",
      "duration": 3.3
    },
    {
      "step": 5,
      "narration": "there exists an element b in G of order five.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "$\\exists\\, b \\in G$ with $\\text{ord}(b) = 5$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_05.mp3",
      "duration": 3.58
    },
    {
      "step": 6,
      "narration": "Let H be the cyclic subgroup generated by a. Then H has order three.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "Let $H = \\langle a \\rangle$, so $|H| = 3$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_06.mp3",
      "duration": 5.57
    },
    {
      "step": 7,
      "narration": "The index of H in G is fifteen over three, which equals five.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "$[G : H] = \\frac{|G|}{|H|} = \\frac{15}{3} = 5$",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_07.mp3",
      "duration": 4.41
    },
    {
      "step": 8,
      "narration": "Now here's the key fact: if the index of a subgroup equals the smallest prime dividing the order of G, then that subgroup is normal.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "If $[G : H]$ is the smallest prime dividing $|G|$, then $H \\trianglelefteq G$.",
      "type": "box",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "Key Fact",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_08.mp3",
      "duration": 8.78
    },
    {
      "step": 9,
      "narration": "The smallest prime dividing fifteen is three, but the index is five, which is bigger than three. So this fact doesn't apply to H directly.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "The smallest prime dividing $15$ is $3$, and $[G:H] = 5 > 3$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_09.mp3",
      "duration": 9.01
    },
    {
      "step": 10,
      "narration": "Instead, let K be the cyclic subgroup generated by b. Then K has order five, and the index of K in G is three.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "Let $K = \\langle b \\rangle$, so $|K| = 5$ and $[G:K] = 3$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_10.mp3",
      "duration": 8.31
    },
    {
      "step": 11,
      "narration": "Three is indeed the smallest prime dividing fifteen.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "$3$ is the smallest prime dividing $|G| = 15$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_11.mp3",
      "duration": 3.53
    },
    {
      "step": 12,
      "narration": "Therefore, K is a normal subgroup of G.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "Therefore $K \\trianglelefteq G$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_12.mp3",
      "duration": 2.93
    },
    {
      "step": 13,
      "narration": "Now, since the orders of H and K are three and five, and gcd of three and five is one:",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "Since $|H| = 3$ and $|K| = 5$, and $\\gcd(3,5) = 1$:",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_13.mp3",
      "duration": 5.94
    },
    {
      "step": 14,
      "narration": "H and K intersect only at the identity.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "H \\cap K = \\{e\\}",
      "type": "math",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_14.mp3",
      "duration": 3.02
    },
    {
      "step": 15,
      "narration": "By the product formula, the size of H K equals three times five over one, which is fifteen. That's the entire group.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "|HK| = \\frac{|H| \\cdot |K|}{|H \\cap K|} = \\frac{3 \\cdot 5}{1} = 15 = |G|",
      "type": "math",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_15.mp3",
      "duration": 8.08
    },
    {
      "step": 16,
      "narration": "So G equals H K, with trivial intersection and K normal.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "So $G = HK$ with $H \\cap K = \\{e\\}$ and $K \\trianglelefteq G$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_16.mp3",
      "duration": 4.69
    },
    {
      "step": 17,
      "narration": "Since K is normal, for any h in H and k in K,",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "Since K is normal, for any h in H and k in K:",
      "type": "text",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_17.mp3",
      "duration": 4.13
    },
    {
      "step": 18,
      "narration": "the commutator h k h inverse k inverse lies in K,",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "hkh^{-1}k^{-1} \\in K",
      "type": "math",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_18.mp3",
      "duration": 4.74
    },
    {
      "step": 19,
      "narration": "and by rearranging, we can show it also lies in H.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "and by rearranging, it also lies in H.",
      "type": "text",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_19.mp3",
      "duration": 3.9
    },
    {
      "step": 20,
      "narration": "So the commutator lies in H intersect K, which is just the identity.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "So $hkh^{-1}k^{-1} \\in H \\cap K = \\{e\\}$.",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_20.mp3",
      "duration": 5.25
    },
    {
      "step": 21,
      "narration": "Therefore h k equals k h. Every element of H commutes with every element of K.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "hk = kh \\quad \\forall\\, h \\in H,\\; k \\in K",
      "type": "math",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_21.mp3",
      "duration": 6.69
    },
    {
      "step": 22,
      "narration": "Now consider the element a b. Since gcd of three and five is one:",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "Consider $ab \\in G$. Since $\\gcd(3,5) = 1$:",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_22.mp3",
      "duration": 4.74
    },
    {
      "step": 23,
      "narration": "the order of a b equals the order of a times the order of b, which is three times five, equals fifteen.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "\\text{ord}(ab) = \\text{ord}(a) \\cdot \\text{ord}(b) = 3 \\cdot 5 = 15",
      "type": "math",
      "mode": "build",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_23.mp3",
      "duration": 7.29
    },
    {
      "step": 24,
      "narration": "So a b generates all of G, which means G is cyclic. And that completes our proof.",
      "latex": "",
      "content": "$\\langle ab \\rangle = G$, so $G$ is cyclic. $\\blacksquare$",
      "type": "mixed",
      "mode": "replace",
      "label": "",
      "audio_path": "jobs/group_order_15/audio/step_24.mp3",
      "duration": 5.57
    }
  ]
}